@<html>
<head>
<title>JWeb : Installation on Linux</title>
</head>

<body>

<hr /> 
<h1>
<img align="left" width="103" height="78" alt="Web Icon" src="web_icon.gif"></a> 
   &nbsp;&nbsp;   JWeb : Installation on Linux 
</h1> 
<p><hr /> <p>

<ul>

<li><h3><a name="general">GENERAL </a></h3>
    <i>JWeb</i> is a point-and-click interface for display and interaction
    with SPIDER images and data written by <b>Dr. Bimal Rath</b>.  
    <i>JWeb</i> is written in Java for use on  Linux  computers. 
<li>     

<p />

<li><h3><a name="installation"> <i>JWeb</i> INSTALLATION </a></h3>

  <ol>
 
  <li><b> <a href="../../spider/docs/spi-register.html">Download</a> and
          <a href="../../spider/docs/spider-inst-linux.html">install</a> 
        the SPIDER/Web distribution</b> and place it in
        an appropriate directory: <i>PARENT-DIR</i>.
  <p />

   The following <i>JWeb</i> related files will be created under: <i>PARENT-DIR/web/jweb</i> 
   <p />
  
    <table border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="4">
      <tr> <th halign="left">File</th>                                               <th halign="left">Contents </th> </tr> 
      <tr><td>src directory</td>                                                     <td><i>JWeb</i> source code</td>        </tr>  
      <tr><td>linux/j2re-1_4_2_06-linux-i586.bin</td>                                <td>JRE install script</td>      </tr>
      <tr><td>linux/jai-1_1_2_01-lib-linux-i586-jre.bin</td>                         <td>JAI install script </td>     </tr>
      <tr><td>linux/linux.WEB.jar</td>                                               <td>Linux <i>JWeb</i> Java archive</td>       </tr>
      <tr><td><a href="../jweb/linux/font.properties">linux/font.properties</a></td> <td>Linux <i>JWeb</i> fonts</td>              </tr>  
      <tr><td><a href="../jweb/linux/jweb.cshrc">linux/jweb.cshrc</a>                <td><i>JWeb</i> 'C' shell environment variables</td> </tr>  
   </table>
   </li>

   <li>Most Linux distributions install a <i>Java Run Time Environment</i> (JRE) by default. 
   However only a few Linux distributions install the 
   <i>Java Advanced Imaging Run Time Environment</i> (JAI) which is needed by <i>JWeb</i>.
   You could add JAI to your Java installation but due to various issues it is
   often simpler to install a second <i>JRE</i> containing <i>JAI</i> as described here.</p>

   <ol>
   <p />

   <li> Access your <i>JWeb</i> directory:    <br />
        <b>cd spider/web/jweb/linux</b>
   </li>
   <p />

   <li> Install the <i>JRE</i> included with <i>JWeb</i> by executing: <br />
       <b> j2re-1_4_2_06-linux-i586.bin</b>  <br />
   </li>
   <p />

   <li> Install <i>JAI</i> in the new Java directory:     <br />
       <b> cd j2re1.4.2_06 </b> <br /> 
       <b> ../jai-1_1_2_01-lib-linux-i586-jre.bin</b>     <br />
   </li>
   <p />

   <li> Return to the <i>JWeb</i> directory:              <br />
        <b> cd .. </b> <br /> 
   </li>
   </ol>
   <p />

    <li> Set necessary environment variables and alias for <i>JWeb</i> usage under Java. <br />
    If you are  using the 'C' shell, edit the first non-comment line in: 
    <a href="../jweb/linux/jweb.cshrc">jweb.cshrc</a> and create a
    <i>$JWEB_DIR</i> environment variable specifying location for <i>JWeb</i> on your system i.e.: <br />
    setenv &nbsp; JWEB_DIR &nbsp;   <b> Enter_path_of_your_JWeb_directory_here </b><br /> 
    Then place the edited contents of <a href="../jweb/linux/jweb.cshrc">jweb.cshrc</a> 
    in the <i>.cshrc</i> startup file in your home directory.  <br /> 
    <li>
    <p />
    <dt> The previous step will also create alias, 'jweb', for starting <i>JWeb</i> with a 
    specified maximum amount <i>-Xmx512m</i> of memory allowed. You may adjust this amount 
    to suit your computer.                                       <br />
    </li>

    <p><li>
    If you are not using a 'C' shell then you will have to alter the last two 
    steps as appropriate for your shell.
    </li></p>

    </ol>

<h3><li><a name="testing"> <i>JWeb</i> TESTING</a></li></h3>
 
    <ul>

    <li>Information on the use of <i>JWeb</i> is given in the <a href="jweb.html"><i>JWeb</i> manual</a>. </li>
    <p />

    <li>Test <i>JWeb</i> : </li>
    <dl>
    <dd><b>jweb </b></dd> 
    <dd><b>USE MOUSE TO SELECT MENU ITEMS FROM PULL-DOWN MENUS </b></dd>
    </dl> 
    <p />

    <li>If you get error messages like:</li>
    <dl>
    <dt> <kbd><code>libXp.so.6:   Cannot open shared object file: No such file or directory</code></kbd></dt>
    <dt> <kbd><code>libXtst.so.6: Cannot open shared object file: No such file or directory</code></kbd></dt> 
    <dt> You may have a 64 bit OS which lacks some 32 bit X Window libraries
        which you will need to install. For distributions which use <i>apt-get</i> this can be done: 
    </dt>
       
    <dd><kbd> sudo apt-get install ibxp6:i386    </kbd></dd>
    <dd><kbd> sudo apt-get install libxtst6:i386 </kbd></dd>
    </dl> 
    <p />


    <li>If you get error messages like:</li> 
    <dl>
    <dt> <kbd><code>Exception in thread "GtkMain" java.lang.UnsatisfiedLinkError: gtkInit ... ....</code></kbd> </dt> 
    <dt>You are not using the Java run time environment packaged with <i>JWeb</i>.  The GNU
          environment that you are trying to use may be defective. </dt>
    </dl>
    </ul>
    <p />


<h3><li><a name="bugs"> BUGS, SUGGESTIONS </a></li></h3>
        
    <dl>
    <p><dt>Send any bug reports or suggestions to: 
       <a href="mailto:spider@@wadsworth.org">spider@@wadsworth.org</a> <br />
    </dl>
  
</ol>

<hr />

<small> 
  Source: jweb-inst-linux.html   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
  Last update: 1/25/17           &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</small>

</body> 
</html>




